Wearing a mask reduces oxygen intake and force you to breathe in your own carbon dioxide (CO2). This is dangerous. Breathing in less oxygen and more CO2 can seriously affect your health. You should know, a mask is not going to protect you against coronavirus, whereas wearing a plastic bag over your head and tie it tight around your neck will, but neither could any oxygen and you would suffocate and die. So, it is important to know that wearing a mask does not absolutely protect you from inhaling the virus. By disturbing your exhalation flow, wearing a mask tends to protect those around you from aerosols in your breath. According to the National Institutes of Health (NIH), it can actually be pretty dangerous. They say that inhaling high levels of CO2 may be life-threatening by causing Hypercapnia (CO2 toxicity), headache, vertigo, double vision, feeling faint, inability to concentrate, tinnitus, seizures, or suffocation due to displacement of air, and gradual brain damage. Healthy people wearing masks are less vulnerable to CO2 toxicity. But such toxicity is most likely to happen to those who are already predisposed to breathing difficulties, caused for example by lung, cardiovascular diseases, or emphysema and anemia, or smokers and obese. It is recommended that you use a cloth mask and only use it when necessary. Make sure your mask feels loose, rather than so tight you really can't breathe. You must remove your mask immediately once you experience sudden feelings of suffocation and breathlessness. People with predisposed to breathing difficulties should be extra cautious, and should make health authority aware.

Wearing a mask reduces oxygen intake and force you to breathe in your own carbon dioxide (CO2). This is dangerous. Breathing in less oxygen and more CO2 can seriously affect your health. You should know, a mask is not going to protect you against coronavirus, whereas wearing a plastic bag over your head and tie it tight around your neck will, but neither could any oxygen and you would suffocate and die. So, it is important to know that wearing a mask does not absolutely protect you from inhaling the virus. By disturbing your exhalation flow, wearing a mask tends to protect those around you from aerosols in your breath. According to the National Institutes of Health (NIH), it can actually be pretty dangerous. They say that inhaling high levels of CO2 may be life-threatening by causing Hypercapnia (CO2 toxicity), headache, vertigo, double vision, feeling faint, inability to concentrate, tinnitus, seizures, or suffocation due to displacement of air, and gradual brain damage. Healthy people wearing masks are less vulnerable to CO2 toxicity. But such toxicity is most likely to happen to those who are already predisposed to breathing difficulties, caused for example by lung, cardiovascular diseases, or emphysema and anemia, or smokers and obese. It is recommended that you use a cloth mask and only use it when necessary. Make sure your mask feels loose, rather than so tight you really can't breathe. You must remove your mask immediately once you experience sudden feelings of suffocation and breathlessness. People with predisposed to breathing difficulties should be extra cautious, and should make health authority aware.

Wearing a mask reduces oxygen intake and force you to breathe in your own carbon dioxide (CO2). This is dangerous. Breathing in less oxygen and more CO2 can seriously affect your health. You should know, a mask is not going to protect you against coronavirus, whereas wearing a plastic bag over your head and tie it tight around your neck will, but neither could any oxygen and you would suffocate and die. So, it is important to know that wearing a mask does not absolutely protect you from inhaling the virus. By disturbing your exhalation flow, wearing a mask tends to protect those around you from aerosols in your breath. According to the National Institutes of Health (NIH), it can actually be pretty dangerous. They say that inhaling high levels of CO2 may be life-threatening by causing Hypercapnia (CO2 toxicity), headache, vertigo, double vision, feeling faint, inability to concentrate, tinnitus, seizures, or suffocation due to displacement of air, and gradual brain damage. Healthy people wearing masks are less vulnerable to CO2 toxicity. But such toxicity is most likely to happen to those who are already predisposed to breathing difficulties, caused for example by lung, cardiovascular diseases, or emphysema and anemia, or smokers and obese. It is recommended that you use a cloth mask and only use it when necessary. Make sure your mask feels loose, rather than so tight you really can't breathe. You must remove your mask immediately once you experience sudden feelings of suffocation and breathlessness. People with predisposed to breathing difficulties should be extra cautious, and should make health authority aware.

Wearing a mask reduces oxygen intake and force you to breathe in your own carbon dioxide (CO2). This is dangerous. Breathing in less oxygen and more CO2 can seriously affect your health. You should know, a mask is not going to protect you against coronavirus, whereas wearing a plastic bag over your head and tie it tight around your neck will, but neither could any oxygen and you would suffocate and die. So, it is important to know that wearing a mask does not absolutely protect you from inhaling the virus. By disturbing your exhalation flow, wearing a mask tends to protect those around you from aerosols in your breath. According to the National Institutes of Health (NIH), it can actually be pretty dangerous. They say that inhaling high levels of CO2 may be life-threatening by causing Hypercapnia (CO2 toxicity), headache, vertigo, double vision, feeling faint, inability to concentrate, tinnitus, seizures, or suffocation due to displacement of air, and gradual brain damage. Healthy people wearing masks are less vulnerable to CO2 toxicity. But such toxicity is most likely to happen to those who are already predisposed to breathing difficulties, caused for example by lung, cardiovascular diseases, or emphysema and anemia, or smokers and obese. It is recommended that you use a cloth mask and only use it when necessary. Make sure your mask feels loose, rather than so tight you really can't breathe. You must remove your mask immediately once you experience sudden feelings of suffocation and breathlessness. People with predisposed to breathing difficulties should be extra cautious, and should make health authority aware.

Wearing a mask reduces oxygen intake and force you to breathe in your own carbon dioxide (CO2). This is dangerous. Breathing in less oxygen and more CO2 can seriously affect your health. You should know, a mask is not going to protect you against coronavirus, whereas wearing a plastic bag over your head and tie it tight around your neck will, but neither could any oxygen and you would suffocate and die. So, it is important to know that wearing a mask does not absolutely protect you from inhaling the virus. By disturbing your exhalation flow, wearing a mask tends to protect those around you from aerosols in your breath. According to the National Institutes of Health (NIH), it can actually be pretty dangerous. They say that inhaling high levels of CO2 may be life-threatening by causing Hypercapnia (CO2 toxicity), headache, vertigo, double vision, feeling faint, inability to concentrate, tinnitus, seizures, or suffocation due to displacement of air, and gradual brain damage. Healthy people wearing masks are less vulnerable to CO2 toxicity. But such toxicity is most likely to happen to those who are already predisposed to breathing difficulties, caused for example by lung, cardiovascular diseases, or emphysema and anemia, or smokers and obese. It is recommended that you use a cloth mask and only use it when necessary. Make sure your mask feels loose, rather than so tight you really can't breathe.
